   <text>
      <body>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39577864">
            <form>
               <orth>Nullaig</orth>
               <pron>[n̪u̜ɫiɡʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[n̪u̜ɫiɡʹ] Note: for Nollaig. Thinks they used to talk of Nullaig Bheag and Nullaig Mhór but doesn’t know much about it. Surmises that Nullaig Bheag may have been Christmas and Nullaig Mhór the New Year.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39584848">
            <form>
               <orth>oidhche</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: Oidhche nan Seachd Suipearan. Note: the longest night in the year.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39595216">
            <form>
               <orth>cèiceach</orth>
               <pron>[cɛ:cɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[cɛ:cɑx] Quot.: falt cèiceach, cloimh chèiceach. Note: unruly hair. (I would have thought “matted” would be nearer the meaning – AJS.)</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37333376">
            <form>
               <orth>badhar</orth>
               <pron>[ˈbɑəð]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈbɑəð] Note: a’ stuth a bhiodh aig na ceannaichean. “Dé an seòrsa badhar a th’aig an duine ud?”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37334384">
            <form>
               <orth>dual</orth>
               <pron>[d̪u̜ɤɫ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[d̪u̜ɤɫ] Quot.: ròpa trì duail. Note: strand in a rope.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37320632">
            <form>
               <orth>cuailean</orth>
               <pron>[ku̟ɤɫɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ku̟ɤɫɑṉ] Quot.: “cuailean fuilt”, “cuailean cloimh”. Note: a lock of hair, (of wool). When used of wool, applied to longish wavy strands.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37314800">
            <form>
               <orth>crot</orth>
               <pron>[kɾɔt̪]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɾɔt̪] Note: a bow, as in a bow-tie.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37327832">
            <form>
               <orth>cnag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: Cuir an cnag air an dorus. Note: locking device on a door. <graphic url="ArnolNCampbellmisc1illust1.jpg" width="200px"/>
            </def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37359512">
            <form>
               <orth>foidh</orth>
               <pron>[f[ɔı]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[f[ɔı]:] Quot.: “Tha e ri foidh.” Note: going from house to house begging for food.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37324376">
            <form>
               <orth>foidhreachd</orth>
               <pron>[fɔıɾɑxk]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[fɔıɾɑxk] Quot.: “Tha e air an fhoidhreachd.” “Tha e air falbh a’ ruith na foidhreachd.” Note: going from house to house begging.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37324808">
            <form>
               <orth>diol-déirc</orth>
               <pron>[dʹwɫdʹe:ɾiɡʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[dʹwɫdʹe:ɾiɡʹ] Note: often applied to a poor person who had nothing.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37311272">
            <form>
               <orth>gabhlach</orth>
               <pron>[ɡɑu̜ɫɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡɑu̜ɫɑx] Quot.: “gabhlach balaich”. Note: a brat, a boy up to no good.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37345832">
            <form>
               <orth>claimhean</orth>
               <pron>[kɫɑ̃ĩvɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɫɑ̃ĩvɑṉ] Note: locking device on a door, either sliding like a bolt or falling down into a slot.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37316240">
            <form>
               <orth>lùdagan</orth>
               <pron>[ɫu̜:d̪əɡɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɫu̜:d̪əɡɑṉ] Note: a hinge.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37328048">
            <form>
               <orth>sneic</orth>
               <pron>[sṉɛ̃c]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[sṉɛ̃c] Note: for opening a door by pressing a lever down with the thumb outside making a length of flat iron, hinged at the inner end, to lift from a slot on the doorpost.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37323512">
            <form>
               <orth>stuig</orth>
               <pron>[st̪iɡʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[st̪iɡʹ] Quot.: “Stuig an cù ann.” Note: set the dog on him.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37315304">
            <form>
               <orth>breacag</orth>
               <pron>[bɾɛkɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bɾɛkɑɡ] Note: bonnach le geadan de losgadh air.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37355768">
            <form>
               <orth>bonnach-bois</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: a thick bannock made between the hands and stood upright beside the fire to bake.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37362176">
            <form>
               <orth>culm</orth>
               <pron>[ku̜ɫu̜m]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ku̜ɫu̜m] Quot.: Tha culm air an latha ’n diugh. Note: a haze.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37349432">
            <form>
               <orth>buigeanag</orth>
               <pron>[bu̜ɡʹəṉɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bu̜ɡʹəṉɑɡ] Note: a type of crab (portan) with a soft back.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37318544">
            <form>
               <orth>déisinneag</orth>
               <pron>[dʹe:ʃĩnʹɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[dʹe:ʃĩnʹɑɡ] Note: a type of “portan”, small and greyish. Not eaten.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37319840">
            <form>
               <orth>an-cheard</orth>
               <pron>[ˈɑṉçɑʴḏ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈɑṉçɑʴḏ] Note: jollity. [NOTES: the turned r used for the symbol which is unclear in the original.]</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37332944">
            <form>
               <orth>cainnean</orth>
               <pron>[kɑ̃nʹɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɑ̃nʹɑṉ] Note: lighted taper.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37356920">
            <form>
               <orth>ceann-bheart</orth>
               <pron>[ˈcɑ̃n̪ɑvȷɑʴsṯ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈcɑ̃n̪ɑvȷɑʴsṯ] Note: headgear. [NOTES: the turned r used for the symbol which is unclear in the original.]</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37353680">
            <form>
               <orth>spiullag</orth>
               <pron>[spȷu̜ɫɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[spȷu̜ɫɑɡ] Quot.: spiullag tombaca. Note: sliver or small piece of tobacco.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37318400">
            <form>
               <orth>balg-snàmh</orth>
               <pron>[bɑɫɑɡsn̪ɑ̃:v]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bɑɫɑɡsn̪ɑ̃:v] Note: airbladder in fish.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37340216">
            <form>
               <orth>briach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Bha a’ chaora sin ann am briach.” Note: said of a sheep which had “òpair” on its legs right up to its belly. Had been stuck or through deep mud.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37315520">
            <form>
               <orth>cnagainneach</orth>
               <pron>[kṉɑ̃ɡĩnʹɔx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kṉɑ̃ɡĩnʹɔx] Note: a hefty type of person.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37358288">
            <form>
               <orth>luirean</orth>
               <pron>[ɫu̜ɾɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɫu̜ɾɑṉ] Quot.: “Mo luirean!” Note: endearing term for a child.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37322000">
            <form>
               <orth>luid</orth>
               <pron>[ɫu̜dʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɫu̜dʹ] Note: big clumsy woman. “Phòs mi luid airson a cuid, Dh’fhalbh a’ chuid ’s dh’fhuirich a’ luid.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37353536">
            <form>
               <orth>butarrais</orth>
               <pron>[ˈbu̜t̪ərɑʃ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈbu̜t̪ərɑʃ] Note: aimsir fhiathaich fhliuch.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm37362320">
            <form>
               <orth>butraiseach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: tìde bhutraiseach.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm154568576">
            <form>
               <orth>burraidh</orth>
               <pron>[bu̜ri]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bu̜ri] Note: a bully.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm154569944">
            <form>
               <orth>burruichgean</orth>
               <pron>[bu̜ru̜çɡʹɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bu̜ru̜çɡʹɑṉ] Note: a bully.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm154569728">
            <form>
               <orth>burruichgeach</orth>
               <pron>[bu̜ru̜çɡʹɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bu̜ru̜çɡʹɑx] Quot.: duine burruichgeach. Note: a bullying person.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm154567496">
            <form>
               <orth>liorcach</orth>
               <pron>[lʹɤɾkɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[lʹɤɾkɑx] Quot.: aodann liorcach. Note: a wrinkled face.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39278528">
            <form>
               <orth>luircean</orth>
               <pron>[ɫu̜ɾcɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɫu̜ɾcɑṉ] Note: applied to a person with a wrinkled face.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39276800">
            <form>
               <orth>preaslaich</orth>
               <pron>[pɾɛsɫiç]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[pɾɛsɫiç] Quot.: Tha preaslaich as an amhaich aige. Note: furrowed, wrinkled skin on neck.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39274856">
            <form>
               <orth>pilleag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “pilleag aodaich”. Note: an article of clothing, a garment.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39273128">
            <form>
               <orth>sturt</orth>
               <pron>[st̪u̜ʴsṯ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[st̪u̜ʴsṯ] Quot.: “Nach ann air a tha a’ sturt.” Note: frowning aspect. [NOTES: the turned r used for the symbol which is unclear in the original.]</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39271040">
            <form>
               <orth>pioc</orth>
               <pron>[pik]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[pik] Quot.: “Chaneil pioc agam.” Note: I have nothing. “Chaneil càil agam.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39269096">
            <form>
               <orth>lòineag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: a piece of fluff, as on a jacket when the hairs on it gather together.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39267584">
            <form>
               <orth>toinndean</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “toinndean cloimh”. Note: a wisp of wool.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39265856">
            <form>
               <orth>toban</orth>
               <pron>[t̪ɔbɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[t̪ɔbɑṉ] Quot.: toban cloimh. Note: a tuft of wool. (Larger than “toinndean” [q.v.].)</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39262976">
            <form>
               <orth>dos</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: dos feur, dos fraoich. Note: a clump of grass, of heather (or bunch of heather – usually used of cut or uprooted heather, grass, etc.)</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39261248">
            <form>
               <orth>bradag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: boirionnach a bhiodh a’ goid.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39259736">
            <form>
               <orth>[ɡʹiˈhɤu̟]</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Bu tu an [ɡʹiˈhɤu̟] (gi-how)”. “’S e fìor [ȷiˈhɤu̟] a th’ann.” Note: common in Lewis. Idiot, person with little sense. “Duine gun chonn.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39257144">
            <form>
               <orth>gilabhram</orth>
               <pron>[ɡıl[ɤu̟]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡıl[ɤu̟]ɾəm] Note: “duine gun chonn”. Also fairly common. Emphasis on the second syllable.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39254984">
            <form>
               <orth>cafan</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: a strong smell, usually bad, which catches one’s breath. “Tha cafan bhon an fheòil sin. Sad as i.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39253256">
            <form>
               <orth>diomb</orth>
               <pron>[dʹũ̟:m]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[dʹũ̟:m] Quot.: “Bha diomb air ris.” Note: He felt displeased with him.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39251312">
            <form>
               <orth>tamhaisg</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Eisd, a thamhaisg!” Note: “Shut up, you idiot!”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39249584">
            <form>
               <orth>bladh</orth>
               <pron>[bɫɤɣ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bɫɤɣ] Quot.: “Duine gun bhladh.” Note: a person with no sense.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39247640">
            <form>
               <orth>sìliche</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “’S e sìliche lacunn a th’ann.” Note: “Duine rudeigin tana bochd a coimhead.”</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39245912">
            <form>
               <orth>gliogair</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: a thin, bony person.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39243536">
            <form>
               <orth>glogaire</orth>
               <pron>[ɡɫɔɡəðə]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡɫɔɡəðə] Note: a big clumsy-looking type.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39241808">
            <form>
               <orth>geòcaire</orth>
               <pron>[ɡʹɔ:kəðə]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡʹɔ:kəðə] Note: glutton. Geòcach – gluttonous.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39239864">
            <form>
               <orth>ciùrrt</orth>
               <pron>[cu̜:rtʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[cu̜:rtʹ] Quot.: “Tha e ciùrrt”. Note: used of a person injured or hurt badly.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39237920">
            <form>
               <orth>fleasgach</orth>
               <pron>[flɛsɡɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[flɛsɡɑx] Note: “duine òg rudeigin grinn na phearsa”.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39236192">
            <form>
               <orth>gasant</orth>
               <pron>[ɡɑsən̪t̪]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡɑsən̪t̪] Quot.: “duine gasant”. Note: duine mór tapaidh.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39234248">
            <form>
               <orth>peitean-bàn</orth>
               <pron>[pɛtʹɑṉbɑ̃:ṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[pɛtʹɑṉbɑ̃:ṉ] Note: a vest made of white blanket cloth (plangaid).</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39232520">
            <form>
               <orth>peitean-beag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: ordinary waistcoat as in a three-piece suit.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39231008">
            <form>
               <orth>peitean-mór</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: a double-breasted short jacket for better wear.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39229496">
            <form>
               <orth>sgiathalaich</orth>
               <pron>[sɡʹıɤhɑɫiç]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[sɡʹıɤhɑɫiç] Quot.: “Bithidh e a’ sgiathalaich thall ’s a bhos.” Note: wandering here and there.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39227480">
            <form>
               <orth>biast</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Chaidh mi na mo bhéist ris.” Note: I went wild at him.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39225752">
            <form>
               <orth>grìleag</orth>
               <pron>[ɡɾı:lɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡɾı:lɑɡ] Note: nighean òg ’s i rudeigin cruinn, tiugh.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39224024">
            <form>
               <orth>blian-mór</orth>
               <pron>[blɑṉmo:ɾ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[blɑṉmo:ɾ] Quot.: “Tha thu ann a’ sin air do bhlian-mór.” Note: lying stretched out on one’s side or almost face down.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39222008">
            <form>
               <orth>blianag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: the underside fish [sic] on a fish, esp. the dogfish in Arnol.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39219632">
            <form>
               <orth>caisean</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: an caisean. Note: Acc. to N.C. “bhiodh iad (nuair a mharbhadh iad caora) a deanamh gearradh sios gach a taobh dhan a mhaodal agus a toirt am pìos so as. Bhiodh iad an uairsin a dathadh a’ chloimh agus a’ bruich an caisean cómhla ris a’ cheanna-chasach [q.v.]”.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39217904">
            <form>
               <orth>ceanna-chasach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Note: the head and trotters of a sheep, usually boiled together.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39216392">
            <form>
               <orth>cearchag</orth>
               <pron>[cɛɾɑxɑɡ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[cɛɾɑxɑɡ] Note: boirionnach beag reamhar.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm39214664">
            <form>
               <orth>aileadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: truaghan bochd gun ailidh [ɑli]. Note: applied to a poor, unfortunate person. A. Campbell (Puilean) says it is “truaghan an ailidh” meaning the same thing.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36115960">
            <form>
               <orth>guin</orth>
               <pron>[ɡũ̟nʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɡũ̟nʹ] Quot.: “Tha guin aige dha.” Note: He has a spite for him. Guineach – spiteful.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36113872">
            <form>
               <orth>cìleach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: caora chìleach, bó chìleach. Note: Partly white, partly greyish.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36112144">
            <form>
               <orth>blàr</orth>
               <pron>[bɫɑ:ɾ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[bɫɑ:ɾ] Quot.: each blàr. Note: a horse with a white patch running from the forehead down the ridge of the nose. Also bó bhlàr, a’ bhó bhlàr.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36109336">
            <form>
               <orth>toilleach</orth>
               <pron>[t̪ɤlʹɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[t̪ɤlʹɑx] Quot.: caora thoilleach. Note: caora eadar a bhi geal agus a bhi glas.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36107392">
            <form>
               <orth>ceol-gàire</orth>
               <pron>[cwɫɡɑ:ðə]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[cwɫɡɑ:ðə] Quot.: “Abair gu robh ceol-gàire ann.” Note: noisy sport, jollity. Also: “Bha e ’na cheol-gàire anns a chuideachd.” – said of a person who entertained the company with his wit and fun-making.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36105304">
            <form>
               <orth>staght</orth>
               <pron>[st̪ɤtʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[st̪ɤtʹ] Quot.: “Staght, a nis!” Note: word used when trying to persuade a cow to stand still.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36103288">
            <form>
               <orth>gonadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Gonadh ort!” Note: mild imprecation.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36101560">
            <form>
               <orth>gonadh</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Bha e air a ghonadh.” Note: said of a person irked and angered by something.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36099832">
            <form>
               <orth>pruimeasail</orth>
               <pron>[pɾw̃məsəl]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[pɾw̃məsəl] Quot.: “Dithis a pruimeasail ri chèile.” Note: talking barely audibly but louder than whispering.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36097816">
            <form>
               <orth>pracas</orth>
               <pron>[pɾɑkəs]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[pɾɑkəs] Quot.: Bha iad a’ pracas ri chèile. Note: making fun, “a’ dibhearsain”.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36095872">
            <form>
               <orth>cùlaire</orth>
               <pron>[ku̟:ləðə]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ku̟:ləðə] Note: sneak.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36094144">
            <form>
               <orth>cùlaireachd</orth>
               <pron>[ku̟:ləðɑk]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ku̟:ləðɑk] Note: sneaking.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36092416">
            <form>
               <orth>cuamhlan</orth>
               <pron>[kũ̜ɑ̃ɫɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kũ̜ɑ̃ɫɑṉ] Quot.: “Bha cuamhlan math ann.” Note: There was a good crowd.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36090472">
            <form>
               <orth>conamhaireachd</orth>
               <pron>[kɔṉɑvɑðɑxk]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɔṉɑvɑðɑxk] Quot.: “Dé a’ chonamhaireachd a th’ort a’ sin?” Note: said to someone who was making a mess of what he was doing, either by design or because he didn’t know how to do it properly.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36087664">
            <form>
               <orth>conablach</orth>
               <pron>[ˈkɔ̃ṉɑbɫɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈkɔ̃ṉɑbɫɑx] Note: gu sonraichte air a chleachdadh airson caora a bhiodh air a milleadh leis na coin.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36085936">
            <form>
               <orth>sgòid</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Bha sgòid air an duine ud.” Note: Bha rud a dhìth air an duine ud, e.g. mentally lacking. A person not able to do things properly.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36084208">
            <form>
               <orth>leth-sgoideach</orth>
               <pron>[lʹɛsɡɔdʹɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[lʹɛsɡɔdʹɑx] Quot.: “duine leth-sgoideach”. Note: applied to a person who was unfortunate in some way – perhaps there was something he had to do but couldn’t do it himself and would get no help.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36082264">
            <form>
               <orth>crabhat</orth>
               <pron>[kɾɑˈvɑt̪]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɾɑˈvɑt̪] Note: used formerly for a scarf.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36080536">
            <form>
               <orth>sgòid</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Bha sgòid mhór air an aodach aice.” Note: said if there was a piece hanging down from the hem of a coat or skirt.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36078808">
            <form>
               <orth>colgant</orth>
               <pron>[kɔɫɔɡɑ̃n̪t̪]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kɔɫɔɡɑ̃n̪t̪] Quot.: duine colgant. Note: duine a bhiodh a’ coimhead uamhasach fiathaich, borb.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36076792">
            <form>
               <orth>cuimrichean</orth>
               <pron>[kw̃məɾiçəṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kw̃məɾiçəṉ] Quot.: “Ach, tha esan eòlach air na cuimrichean.” Note: the area round about, the immediate neighbourhood.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36074776">
            <form>
               <orth>sealghan</orth>
               <pron>[ʃɑɫɑɣɑṉ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ʃɑɫɑɣɑṉ] Quot.: “Cha teid mìr dheth ri do shealghan.” Note: You won’t get a bite of it to eat.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36072832">
            <form>
               <orth>siogach</orth>
               <pron>[ʃıɡɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ʃıɡɑx] Quot.: duine siogach, beathach siogach. Note: tana, bochd.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36070024">
            <form>
               <orth>gliuthach</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: “Sad as e. Chaneil ann ach gliuthach.” Note: applied to a fish so poor as to be rejected.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36068296">
            <form>
               <orth>cuineal</orth>
               <pron>[kũ̟nʹɑɫ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[kũ̟nʹɑɫ] Quot.: Tha e an còmhnaidh a’ cuineal. Note: a’ gearain.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36066352">
            <form>
               <orth>tonnag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: tonnag langainn. Note: a small young ling, not the “tonnag” found in rocky pools inshore.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36064624">
            <form>
               <orth>tarrachd</orth>
               <pron>[t̪ɑrɔxk]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[t̪ɑrɔxk] Quot.: “Chaneil ann dheth ach tarrachd duine.” “Chaneil ann dheth ach tarrachd.” Note: a good-for-nothing sort of person. A lazy person who won’t work.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36062536">
            <form>
               <orth>àmhailt</orth>
               <pron>[ɑ̃:vilʹtʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ɑ̃:vilʹtʹ] Quot.: “Tha e lan amhailtean [sic].” Note: He is full of tricks. Duine àmhailteach.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36060448">
            <form>
               <orth>cas-gun-rath</orth>
               <pron>[ˈkɑsɡəˈrɑ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[ˈkɑsɡəˈrɑ] Note: “duine gun dòigh”.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36058720">
            <form>
               <orth>leanamhainn</orth>
               <pron>[lʹɛ̃ṉɑvĩnʹ]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[lʹɛ̃ṉɑvĩnʹ] Quot.: “Tha e ’ga do leanamhainn.” Note: He is following you.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36056776">
            <form>
               <orth>leanamhainneach</orth>
               <pron>[lʹɛ̃ṉɑvĩnʹɑx]</pron>
            </form>
            <def>[lʹɛ̃ṉɑvĩnʹɑx] Quot.: “Tha e glé leanamhainneach.” Note: could be used of an illness or anything going on for a long time.</def>
         </entry>
         <entry xml:id="AJSmith_ArnolNCampbellmisc1-idm36054832">
            <form>
               <orth>sgromag</orth>
            </form>
            <def>Quot.: sgromag air uachdair cloich. Note: a crust.</def>
         </entry>
      </body>
   </text>
